Problem 1¶

We are looking at data from a gamma-ray satellite orbiting in low Earth orbit. It takes a reading of the number of particles detected every 100 milliseconds in an approximately 90-minute orbit. While it is looking for gamma-ray bursts, virtually all of the particles detected are background cosmic rays.

The data has four columns with more than 25 million rows. Column 1: time (gps seconds). Column 2: solar phase (deg) showing position of sun relative to orbit. Column 3: Earth longitude (deg) showing position of spacecraft relative to ground. Column 4: particle counts.

In [160]:
hf = h5py.File('gammaray_lab4.h5', 'r')
data = np.array(hf.get('data'))
hf.close()

Section 1.1

Below are a few plots so we can understand our data. In the 2D histogram of earth phase vs particle count, we see how particle count depends on earth phase. This is because the density of the points changes as the earth phase increases. In the 2D histogram of solar phase vs particle count, we see how particle count doesn't depend on solar phase. This is because the density of the points remain constant as the solar phase increase. In our semi-log histogram of time vs earth phase and time vs solar phase, we see regular patterns of triangles. This tells us the earth and solar phases are cyclic which means the phase goes from 0 to 360 at regular intervals. We see this in our semi-log plot of time vs particle count where the plot has a somewhat triangle-shaped pattern which means we can expect to see a certain number of particle counts in a single orbit. These are the general patterns we notice.

Now, some of these plots show irregularities which could attribute to sigma contamination. For example, we notice a sudden increase of particle counts at roughly 320 degrees in our 2D histogram of earth phase vs particle count. We can see how the distribution was slowly decaying in the region from 0 to approximately 320 degrees but suddenly increases afterwards to slowly decay again. Another irregularity is in our histogram of particle count frequency. Here, we notice spikes at 11 and 21 which are apparent in the semi-log histogram of particle count frequency. This could be the result of sigma contamination in our data especially since we know the particle count is dependent on earth phase.

Our plan to build a background pdf() is to look at the histogram of the particle count frequency. Since we are observing gamma-ray bursts, we expect an integer number of counts. This means our background pdf() should be a Poisson distribution. So, we would take the mean of the particle counts to find a $\mu$ and its corresponding distribution.

Section 1.2

The background is not consistent with the data set. We know this because the particle count is dependent on the earth phase. In the plot below, we notice a discontinuity at approximately 320 degrees. Again, we notice how the particle count is steadily decaying in the region from 0 to 320 degrees at which the particle count suddenly increases to decay again. This shows sigma contamination since the mean is constantly shifting since particle count is dependent on earth phase. So the background changes because of the earth phase.

Section 1.3

Now, we want to create a model with time dependence. From above, we can see how the plot somewhat follows a decaying exponential function if we ignore the discontinuity. After the discontinuity, the plot seems to follow a decaying exponential function again. We will use this type of distribution as our base for our model. So our model will be in the form $y = A e ^{Bt} + C$. Below is the model for the exponential within the region from 0 to approximately 320 degrees.

Problem 2¶

Here, we will be looking at a stack of ten simulated telescope images. Our goal is to find the faintest stars and a transient (which is equivalent to a super novae). I will pursue the goal of finding the faintest stars while my lab partner will pursue the other goal of finding the transient which only appears in one image. We are told the images are square with 200 pixel on a side.

Section 2.1

Here, we want to download the ten simulated telescope images. We follow the same process as the previous part but we aren't given the keys of the data set. We can get these keys by using .keys(). Below, we print the keys and store the data sets.

Section 2.2

From each of the ten images, we see outliers appear after an intensity of 30. These intensities are most likely related to the transient which I am not exploring. Otherwise, a majority of the data lies in the region before an intensity of 30 which is where I would find the dimmest stars. There is signal contamination in the pdf() from all of the zero intensity spots in the image which are most likely empty space. This is because I am interested in finding dimmest stars but the zero intensity spots would affect the signal and contribute nothing of value to me. Now, we notice how the images doesn't change too drastically which means the background isn't time dependent. Also, each pdf() shows the background is consistent spatially. This is because a majority of the image is empty space which is associated with zero intensity. However, we do see some bright spots too.

Section 2.3

Here, we will execute our plan to create our background pdf(). As a reminder, our plan was to average the intensity across the ten images to create our background pdf(). Below, our background pdf() of the average intensity happens to be a Gaussian distribution with $\sigma = 0.991$ and $\mu = 0.033$. Using this distribution, we will hunt for the signal which are associated with the dimmest stars. This can be achieved by analyzing the tails of the Gaussian distribution. Specifically, the dimmest star will be the leftmost point in the Gaussian distribution.

In [312]:
intensity_avg = []
for i in range(200):
    for j in range(200):
        for k in range(9):
            avg = np.mean(images[i,j,k])
            intensity_avg.append(avg)
            
plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
plt.hist(intensity_avg, bins=1000)
plt.title("Background Probability Density of Average Intensity", fontsize=24)
plt.xlabel("Intensity", fontsize=18)
plt.ylabel("Counts", fontsize=18)
plt.xlim(-4, 4);

# calculate associated sigma and mean
sigma = np.std(intensity_avg)
mean = np.mean(intensity_avg)
print('We get a sigma of {0:1.3f}'.format(sigma), 'and a mean of {0:1.3f}'.format(mean))

We get a sigma of 0.991 and a mean of 0.033

Section 2.4

Even though my lab partner and I had different pdf() despite using the same data is because we were pursuing different goals of looking for the faintest stars or the transient. This means our statistical questions were different but we could use the same data to answer our question. In this case, I used the data to find signals for dimmest stars while my lab partner used the data to find signals for brightest stars. Thus, our background pdf() varied since we extracted and plotted data to answer our different statistical questions. Specifically, I had to look at the noise while my partner looked for and compared the brightest stars in every image.
